{'query': 'Does the organization have processes and mechanisms for restricting access to system components and cardholder data that are defined and understood?', 'context': 'Question: Is timely deprovisioning, revocation, or modification of user access to the organizations systems, information assets, and data implemented upon any change in status of employees, contractors, customers, business partners, or involved third parties? | Answer: Yes | Details: We have role-based access control and abide by "need-to-know" guidelines. When new employees are added or when existing employees change roles, the employee's role determines which systems they are granted access to and at what access level. Access privileges are reviewed at least yearly and when an employee changes roles or status. Only select and authorized members of the engineering team have access to the production environment where customer data is located. | Category: Application', 'text': 'Yes.

We have role-based access control and abide by "need-to-know" guidelines. When new employees are added or when existing employees change roles, the employee's role determines which systems they are granted access to and at what access level. Access privileges are reviewed at least yearly and when an employee changes roles or status. Only select and authorized members of the engineering team have access to the production environment where customer data is located.

Restricting access to system components and cardholder data is implemented through regular security assessments and penetration testing, which identify vulnerabilities and provide recommendations for remediation. Additionally, we have a formal incident response plan in place that outlines procedures for responding to security incidents involving sensitive data or systems. Our chief information security officer (CISO) is responsible for overseeing the implementation of these measures and ensuring that all employees understand their roles in protecting our organization's assets.'}
